kanji.components: 手: hand 斤: axe; 1.32 lb; catty; counter for loaves of bread; axe radical (no. 69)
kanji.koohii1: It´s the latest Japanese game show: Forudo! Contestants are given a sheet of paper and are told to fold it into a complex origami shape. If they´re not done in 60 seconds/ a huge axe descends from the ceiling and chops their work in half. Contestants know to recoil their hands from the falling axe/ but some have been so absorbed in folding/ they ignore the buzzer and get their fingers chopped off.
kanji.koohii2: Fold some origami into the shape of an axe with your fingers. It´s even as sharp/ so watch out for paper cuts!

kanji_info.image_description: A giant hand wielding an axe, dramatically chopping down a tall, bendy tree, its branches folding under the force of the blow.

kanji_info.image_description: A whimsical close-up of a hand, each fingertip delightfully decorated with a tiny, delicious-looking candy, pointing towards a delectable array of sweets.

kanji.koohii1: If you end up in failure/ you give money to the taskmaster to train you.
kanji.koohii2: The shell who was defeated before (defeat (#63)) is being chastised by the taskmaster for his failure to win.

kanji_info.image_description: A cartoon shellfish is sadly slumped over, defeated, with a large folding chair looming over it as if it represents the weight of failure and a big hit in a battle.

kanji.koohii1: Young taskmaster is learning numbers by watching women haul sacks of rice past him. 'One... two... four! No/ wrong! Go back/ go back!'.
kanji.koohii2: Women toil in the rice fields carrying heavy sacks of rice to be numbered and counted by the taskmaster.

kanji_info.image_description: A playful scene where a woman is counting grains of rice, using an old-fashioned abacus made of rice and each bead showing a number. The background features a fun whimsical landscape.

kanji.koohii1: Once upon a time/ the children were forced to eat their salad every day.
kanji.koohii2: For those who don´t know the expression/ 'salad days' means the time of one´s youth. (originally from Shakespeare´s Antony and Cleopatra - see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salad_days). I suspect Heisig chose 'salad' as the name for the radical just for this phrase...

kanji_info.image_description: A cheerful illustration of a giant sun rising behind a stylized number twenty, casting long shadows over ancient ruins, symbolizing the passage of time from a bright new day in the past to the present day.

short_text_with_quiz.text_japanese: 数人の指導員が、電気自動車の発展に対して指導をしています。彼らの目指すものは、この分野の発展です。サポートとして、研修の人数を数えています。物音はありましたが、何とか全員を数えることができました。指導員たちは、この仕事を快適だと感じています。
short_text_with_quiz.text_english: Several instructors are providing guidance towards the development of electric vehicles.  Their aim is the expansion of this sector. To support this, they are counting the number of participants in the training program.  They somehow managed to count everyone despite some background sounds. The instructors find this work pleasant.

song_lyrics.lyrics_japanese:
十まで数えることを目指す、
指導員の指導を受けて、
数字を一つずつ数える、
目標に向かって頑張る。

数人が周りにいる、
人数はたくさん、
快適な小屋の中で、
何とか一緒に学ぶ。

自然の音を数える、
生チーズはご褒美、
学習のサポートをするために、
借金はない、ただ喜び。

数字を指す、
数多くの数字を学ぶ、
発展を目指す、
指導員の助けで。

車の数を数える、
電気自動車が見える、
理解するために、
物事の量を。

数えることを学び、頑張ることを学ぶ、
指導が与えられ、成功するために、
あらゆる困難に逆らって、成功する、
今の目標を、超える。
song_lyrics.lyrics_english_translation:
I aim to count to ten, 
With the instructor's guidance,
Learning numbers, one by one,
Towards my goal, I strive.

Several people are around,
The number of people is great,
In this pleasant cabin,
We learn, somehow together. 

Counting the sounds of nature,
Fresh cheese is the treat,
